# Sitemap lastModified — keep it honest

## Rule

When you modify **any file that affects the rendered content of a page** (layout, page components, dictionary strings, shared components like header/footer/CTA banner, blog data), you **must** also bump the `STATIC_PAGES_LAST_MOD` date in `src/app/sitemap.ts` to today's date (YYYY-MM-DD format).

## Why

Google uses `<lastmod>` in sitemaps to prioritize crawling. If the date never changes, or changes on every build (via `new Date()`), Google learns to ignore it — hurting crawl efficiency and re-indexing speed for genuinely updated pages.

A manually maintained date is the most reliable signal: it only changes when content actually changes.

## What to update

```ts
// src/app/sitemap.ts — top of file
const STATIC_PAGES_LAST_MOD = "YYYY-MM-DD"; // ← bump to today's date
```

## When to bump

- Editing page content or metadata (titles, descriptions, OG tags)
- Changing dictionary strings that appear on pages
- Adding/removing/reordering navigation links
- Modifying shared layout components (header, footer, CTA banner)
- Adding or editing blog posts (blog posts have their own per-post `date` field, but bump `STATIC_PAGES_LAST_MOD` too if the blog index page layout changed)

## When NOT to bump

- Pure code refactors that don't change rendered output
- Dependency updates
- Dev tooling / config changes
- Changes to files outside the page rendering pipeline (API routes, scripts, etc.)
